        <div class="blog-article-body">

            <p class="blog-lead">
                Before you send a PDF outside your organization, anything you
                don't want the recipient to see needs to be properly redacted —
                not just covered up. Here's the difference, and how to do it
                right.
            </p>

            <h2>Covering text with a black box is not redaction</h2>
            <p>
                A common mistake: drawing a black rectangle over sensitive
                text in a PDF viewer or image editor and assuming it's gone.
                It isn't. The underlying text is often still embedded in the
                document and can be recovered by selecting and copying it,
                or by simply removing the box layer in an editor. This has
                caused real, public data leaks — law firms, government
                agencies, and news outlets have all published "redacted"
                PDFs where the hidden text was still extractable.
            </p>
            <p>
                Real redaction permanently deletes the underlying text and
                any image data beneath the mark, not just paints over it.
            </p>

            <h2>What to redact before sending a PDF externally</h2>
            <ul>
                <li>Social Security numbers, national ID numbers, account numbers</li>
                <li>Dates of birth and other personal identifiers</li>
                <li>Salary figures, pricing, or commercially sensitive numbers</li>
                <li>Names of third parties not relevant to the recipient</li>
                <li>Internal notes, comments, or metadata not meant for external eyes</li>
            </ul>

            <h2>Step-by-step: Redact a PDF properly</h2>
            <ol>
                <li>Go to <a href="/redact-pdf">PdfToolStack Redact PDF</a></li>
                <li>Upload the document</li>
                <li>Draw a redaction box over each piece of sensitive text or image content</li>
                <li>Apply the redactions — this permanently removes the underlying content, not just the visible layer</li>
                <li>Download the redacted PDF and verify the text can no longer be selected or searched</li>
            </ol>
            <p>
                Always double-check by trying to select or search for the
                redacted text in the downloaded file before sending it.
            </p>

            <h2>Don't forget metadata</h2>
            <p>
                Redacting visible text isn't the whole job. PDF metadata can
                include the author's name, the software used, edit history,
                and sometimes comments or tracked changes that were never
                meant to leave your organization. Strip metadata as part of
                your redaction workflow, especially for documents heading to
                opposing counsel, regulators, or the press.
            </p>

